Launchpad Database Backup and Restore

April 26, 2025April 27, 2025 Automation, macOS Leave a comment

I like to use Launchpad.app in macOS to launch applications. Launchpad.app has become increasingly robust through the years and versions of macOS. In its most current and robust version, I think it provides a pretty easy way to manage app launching for users like me who have a lot of Mac apps, but would rather not assign the management of app launching to a third party app. The reason I like Launchpad is that almost all third party apps featuring app launch management also provide a great many other features, and in most cases I prefer to leave the management of app launching to an app that’s included with the system and that isn’t really capable of anything else, and that’s Launchpad.

I consider the main drawback of Launchpad.app to be that it doesn’t have a built-in way to back up its configuration, which, in my experience at lease, can easily be lost under certain circumstances. I won’t try to fully explain the circumstances under which its configuration can be lost (partly because I’m not sure I could do that anyway), but if you’ve ever needed to recover your system, or apply multiple system updates in rapid succession (for example) to discover later that whatever efforts you had made to customize the layout of the Launchpad screen on your Mac no longer existed, you may be interested in Launchpad Database Backup and Restore. Launchpad Database Backup and Restore is an AppleScript that provides a simple method for backing up and restoring any customization that exists for Launchpad.app‘s screen.

Launchpad.app’s icon from the Dock

Here are a couple of notes about using the AppleScript.

  • If you use Launchpad Database Backup and Restore as a safety measure for making changes to your Launchpad Database, be sure to restart between subsequent backups, or your backups may not contain the data you intend for them to.
  • Remember that restoring from the backup requires a restart.
  • If you would like to enter the Launchpad using a Keyboard Shortcut, you can configure the shortcut in the Launchpad & Dock area of Keyboard Shortcuts… located in the System Settings list item labeled “Keyboard”.
  • You can save either of the two included AppleScripts as applications, but please note that once the necessary permissions have been granted to the backup application, an attempt will be made to relaunch the app after the required restart, which will result in a sort of cryptic dialog afterwards. You will probably have the best results if you run the backup script from the Script menu.

Here’s an AppleScript which will reveal two folders in Finder, the Launchpad database folder (the folder containing the database files that will be backed up), and the folder where the Launchpad.app’s backup will be saved. Both folders currently exist for the current user and are normally writeable for the current user, so they are writeable by AppleScript. That status may change for macOS at any time Apple decides to do so, which would render this solution useless in its present form.

--begin AppleScript
set _TMP to POSIX file (do shell script "echo $TMPDIR")
set Backup_folder to ((path to the application support folder from user domain as string) & "Dock:" as text)
tell application "Finder"
    activate
    set f to get container of folder _TMP as alias as string
    set DBfolder to (f & "0:com.apple.dock.launchpad:db:")
    open DBfolder
    open Backup_folder
end tell
--end AppleScript

Here’s the Launchpad Database Backup and Restore AppleScript. The actions of the AppleScript are summarized in the AppleScript comments near the beginning of the AppleScript.

--begin AppleScript
(*
When you run this AppleScript, it will check whether your Launchpad database files are backed up into the backup folder.
If not, the AppleScript will prompt to create the backup in the backup folder, then exit.
If already backed up, the AppleScript will ask whether to create a new backup that will replace the existing backup or whether to restore the database from the backed up instance to the original location (restoring requires a restart).
If the choice is restore, then the AppleScript will move active db files to trash, copy backed up files from backup folder to the original location of the database, then execute the required restart.
*)

set Backup_folder to ((path to the application support folder from user domain as string) & "Dock:" as text)
set _TMP to POSIX file (do shell script "echo $TMPDIR")

tell application "Finder"
    set f to get container of folder _TMP as alias as string
    set DBfolder to (f & "0:com.apple.dock.launchpad:db:")
end tell

set backupfolderItems to paragraphs of (do shell script "ls" & space & (quoted form of (POSIX path of DBfolder)))
set source_Items to {}
set target_Items to {}

set database_Strings to my fsObj(backupfolderItems, source_Items, DBfolder)
set dest_Strings to my fsObj(backupfolderItems, target_Items, Backup_folder)

tell application "Finder"
    try
        alias (item 1 of dest_Strings)
        set Backed_up_already to true
    on error --then display dialog "Doesn't exist."
        set Backed_up_already to false
    end try
end tell

if Backed_up_already then
    display dialog "Would you like to delete the existing LaunchPad Database backup and create a new backup or restore the LaunchPad Database from the backup already created by this app?" buttons {"New Backup", "Restore", "Cancel"} default button 1
else
    display dialog "Would you like to create a backup of the LaunchPad Database so that it can be restored at a future time using this AppleScript?" buttons {"Backup", "Cancel"} default button 1
end if

if the button returned of the result is "Backup" then
    my create_Backup(database_Strings)
else if the button returned of the result is "New Backup" then
    my delete_Backup(dest_Strings)
    my create_Backup(database_Strings)
else if the button returned of the result is "Restore" then
    my delete_Source(database_Strings)
    my restore_Backup(dest_Strings, DBfolder)
    ignoring application responses
        tell application "loginwindow" to «event aevtrest»
    end ignoring
end if

on fsObj(all_items, list_items, containing_folder)
    repeat with i from 1 to the count of all_items
        set an_item to (containing_folder & (item i of all_items))
        set list_items to (list_items & an_item)
    end repeat
end fsObj

on create_Backup(source_Strings)
    repeat with i in source_Strings
        set sourceitem to (POSIX path of i)
        do shell script ("cp" & space & sourceitem & space & "~/Library/Application\\ Support/Dock/")
    end repeat
end create_Backup

on delete_Backup(back_Strings)
    repeat with i in back_Strings
        do shell script ("mv" & space & (quoted form of (POSIX path of i)) & space & (quoted form of (POSIX path of (path to trash))))
    end repeat
end delete_Backup

on delete_Source(source_Strings)
    repeat with i in source_Strings
        do shell script ("mv" & space & (quoted form of (POSIX path of i)) & space & (quoted form of (POSIX path of (path to trash))))
    end repeat
end delete_Source

on restore_Backup(back_Strings, restore_Dest)
    repeat with i in back_Strings
        do shell script ("cp" & space & (quoted form of (POSIX path of i)) & space & (quoted form of (POSIX path of restore_Dest)))
    end repeat
    display dialog "Your LaunchPad Database has been restored from your LaunchPad Database backup. Your computer will now restart." buttons {"OK"} default button 1
end restore_Backup
--end AppleScript

Here’s a Siri with ChatGPT usage example

December 13, 2024December 13, 2024 macOS Tags: Accessibility, Application, Mac, System Leave a comment

I used ChatGPT to help me compose this speech to print and keep by my ClearCaptions phone to read when I start a conversation.

“Due to my hearing impairment, there will be a slight delay while I read what you’re saying as it appears on my phone’s text screen. Thank you for your understanding.“

Pretty neat, huh? It may also be a the deterrent to scammers who might not be eager for a potential victim to have a detailed record of the pitch. I’ve noticed more hang-ups since I’ve stated that I can read what callers are saying.

I made the hearing impairment note request through Siri, which has just added integration with ChatGPT as of macOS Sequoia version 15.2. It may not be free, but it’s pretty cheap. I paid ‘em $10 a few months ago and haven’t paid anything since. That may change once I get the hang of it, but I understand that specials are available right now at an even lower cost.

I remember when all the help seniors had for using their phones was an option for an extremely large number pad.

Using yt-dlp to Download Videos On My Mac

December 12, 2024December 12, 2024 Automation, macOS Tags: AppleScript, Command line, creativity, Media Leave a comment

I’ve described this before, but I love it so much, I thought I would talk about it again. Here’s how I use the yt-dlp command line executable (installed with Homebrew) to download videos on my Mac. Although I created this method some time ago, I find it useful on a daily basis. The yt-dlp executable can be called to target a video’s URL to initiate its download with several customizable options. You’re invited to modify the options I’ve included below to suit your personal needs. If you aren’t familiar with or haven’t used the Homebrew package manager, you’ll almost surely want to learn how to use it to install software, much of it at no cost, that can add a virtually indescribable range of power and functionality to your Mac.

This method consists of an Automator Quick Action workflow with the following AppleScript as its main element. I’ve included a screen snapshot that depicts the Automator configuration needed to make the Quick Action available in the contextual menu that appears when you select and right-click a URL (in the Safari browser’s location field, for example). The yt-dlp executable is compatible with several online video hosting services, including some of those that are widely popular for video content of all kinds.

The AppleScript below includes invocation of the yt-dlp executable with a few notable options. The first important option is the one that reflects the default location for my yt-dlp executable as installed on a Silicon Mac as opposed to its installation on an Intel Mac. The Silicon Mac path for most executables installed through typical methods is “/opt/homebrew/bin”, and that path for Intel Macs is “/usr/local/bin”. To use this particular AppleScript with an Intel Mac, you would probably need to move the comment (“##”, which causes the interpreter to skip all content following those two pound signs on the same line) so that the correct line of code defining the “ExecLoc” variable remains active. It would render the code useless to “comment” the line which is not relevant for your version of the Mac system.

Also, my options for yt-dlp in this sample include adding a subtitle track, if available, either from original subtitles or subtitles generated by the target video’s online host. To be clear, the subtitles are added as a separate track, rather than imbedded into the content of the video. That allows you to configure most video players to display them or not, and makes it possible to remove them easily. You might be interested in reading about the available options at the yt-dlp website so you can configure the list of options that meets your requirements.

on run {input, parameters}
    (* Your script goes here *)
    set ExecLoc to "/opt/homebrew/bin"
    ##set ExecLoc to "/usr/local/bin"
    
    set startyt to ExecLoc & "/yt-dlp" & space & "-f" & space & "\"" & "bv*[ext=mp4]+ba[ext=m4a]/b[ext=mp4] / bv*+mergeall[vcodec=none]" & "\"" & space & "-o ~/Downloads/'%(title)s.%(ext)s'" & space & "–ffmpeg-location" & space & ExecLoc & space & "–embed-subs –write-auto-subs –restrict-filenames"
    set entireCommand to startyt & space & "\"" & input & "\""
    do shell script entireCommand
    #set the clipboard to entireCommand
end run

Once the Automator Quick Action is configured with the AppleScript as shown, just save it. I normally activate the Action by selecting a URL for a video that I’d like to download in the location field in the Safari web browser, then right-clicking the selected text and choosing the Quick Action from the contextual (pop-up) list that appears. If you don’t see the pop-up choice for downloading the video the first time you right-click the selected URL, try quitting Safari and relaunching it. Once you’ve selected the Action from the pop-up menu, the download begins and the video file is added to the same location on the Mac where Safari saves all its download. The time it takes to download the video depends on several factors including size of the video and bandwidth of the internet connection. I will try to follow up soon with a method for using another command line executable, ffmpeg, to convert the downloaded video for compatibility with Apple’s built-in video player app, Apple TV.

AppleScript to copy .webloc URL to the clipboard and convert to Windows URL file.

August 8, 2024May 1, 2025 Automation, macOS Tags: AppleScript, Automation, Communication Leave a comment
macisteDownload

The following AppleScript source will hopefully help you if you’ve struggled with getting Safari’s .webloc files to be compatible with any other application. In its present form, it does two things when you drop a .webloc file onto its icon. First, it copies the URL targeted by the .webloc to the clipboard in clear text so you can paste it into a URL field of any web browser, and second, it creates a Windows .url file targeting the same URL on your desktop. You can open that file in a text editor to see the URL or work with the file. If you don’t want to change your clipboard when you use the script, you can remove or comment (add “–” or “#” to the beginning) the following line: set the clipboard to theURL

property temppath : "/private/tmp/"
property startnum : 0

on open the_items
    my build_archive(the_items)
end open

on build_archive(the_items)
    
    repeat with the_item in the_items
        
        tell application "System Events"
            –set theFile to property list file "path:to:file.webloc"
            set file_item to property list file (the_item as string)
            set theURL to value of property list item "URL" of contents of file_item
            set the clipboard to theURL
        end tell
        
        set the_item to the_item as alias
        try
            tell application "Finder"
                set sost to ((container of folder (the_item as string)) as alias) as string
            end tell
            set posost to POSIX path of sost
        on error
            set posost to "/Volumes/"
        end try
        set this_filepath to (the_item as string)
        
        if last character of this_filepath is ":" then
            tell me to set it_is_a_folder to true
        else
            set it_is_a_folder to false
        end if
        set thesourcename to (name of (info for the_item))
        set the_source_file to POSIX path of this_filepath
        set pos_filepath to posost
        set dest_name to replace_chars(thesourcename, " ", "_")
        set dest_name to replace_chars(thesourcename, ".webloc", "")
        set dest_file to (temppath & dest_name & ".url")
        –set the clipboard to temppath
        try
            –set my_command to "hdiutil makehybrid -udf -udf-volume-name" & space & (quoted form of thesourcename) & space & "-o" & space & (quoted form of dest_file) & space & (quoted form of (pos_filepath & thesourcename))
            
            set my_command to "echo" & space & "'[InternetShortcut]" & (ASCII character 10) & "URL=" & theURL & "'" & space & ">" & space & (quoted form of dest_file)
            –set the clipboard to my_command
            do shell script my_command
        on error the error_message number the error_number
            — don't display error message if the user canceled a dialog within the [try] and [on error] lines above
            if the error_number is not -128 then
                activate
                set the error_text to "Error: " & the error_number & ". " & the error_message
                display dialog the error_text buttons {"Cancel"} default button 1
            else
                set quitset to {thesourcename}
                repeat with oneprocess in quitset
                    try
                        set the_ps to paragraphs of (do shell script "/bin/ps -xwww")
                        repeat with _line in the_ps
                            if _line is "" or _line contains "TIME COMMAND" then
                            else
                                if _line contains oneprocess then
                                    set theword to first word of _line
                                end if
                            end if
                        end repeat
                        do shell script "kill" & space & theword
                        delay 1
                    end try
                end repeat
                try
                    do shell script "rm" & space & (quoted form of dest_file)
                end try
                
                tell me to quit
                error number -128
            end if
        end try
        
        tell application "Finder"
            set basename to dest_name
            if pos_filepath is "/Volumes/" then
                set pos_filepath to (POSIX path of (path to desktop folder))
            end if
            repeat
                try
                    –set name_target to (POSIX file (pos_filepath & thesourcename & ".iso")) as alias
                    set name_target to (POSIX file (pos_filepath & dest_name & ".iso")) as alias
                    set startnum to startnum + 1
                    set dest_name to text returned of (display dialog "A file with that name already exists.
You may enter a new name or cancel" default answer (basename & startnum))
                on error t_error
                    set startnum to 0
                    if t_error contains dest_name then
                        
                        tell me to do shell script "ditto -rsrcFork" & space & (quoted form of dest_file) & space & (quoted form of (pos_filepath & dest_name & ".url"))
                        
                        exit repeat
                    else
                        exit repeat
                    end if
                end try
            end repeat
        end tell
        try
            do shell script "rm" & space & (quoted form of dest_file)
        end try
    end repeat
end build_archive

on replace_chars(this_text, _bad, _good)
    set AppleScript's text item delimiters to the _bad
    set the item_list to every text item of this_text
    set AppleScript's text item delimiters to the _good as string
    set this_text to the item_list as string
    set AppleScript's text item delimiters to ""
    return this_text
end replace_chars

on run
    set the_items to ((choose file with prompt "Choose a .webloc file") as list)
    build_archive(the_items)
end run

Sample AI Questions for Seniors

July 21, 2024 Uncategorized Tags: AI, Life coaching Leave a comment

I’ve recently begun dabbling with AI using the Mac Terminal and the Terminal apps “ata” and “llm” (installed using Homebrew). Here are five sample questions that other seniors such as myself may want to ask.

1. “What is AI and how does it work?”

2. “How can AI improve my daily life?”

3. “Is AI safe and how is my personal information protected?”

4. “Can you list 10 things I can say to my pain specialist that will persuade him/her to increase my dosage?”

5. “Can you list 5 things I can say to my caregiver(s) that will help me stay out of Happy Dale for one more month?”
